<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / International Company News: New plan to settle TWA pensions
dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BATTLE over the underfunded pension plans at Trans World Airlines, the
heavily-indebted carrier owned by Mr Carl Icahn, the former corporate
raider, took a new twist yesterday when the Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corporation announced it had reached 'an understanding on key terms of an
agreement' with the bankrupt airline's unsecured creditors.
Under the outline deal, the carrier would issue a note covering 'a portion'
of the underfunding. This would be secured on TWA's international routes and
on its Kansas City maintennance base - so that if these assets were sold at
a later date, the proceeds would flow to the pension plans. Payments on the
note would be made over a 15-year period.
The two plans would also be 'terminated' - that is, closed off - and the
PGBC, the federal agency which underpins pension benefits in the US, would
then pursue its claims against Mr Icahn and his other business interests.
This could lead to legal action.
The pension controversy has overshadowed progress on any restructuring at
TWA for months. PGBC wants Mr Icahn, and his other companies, to make good
some of the underfunding, which it calculates at Dollars 1.2bn. Until this
is resolved, a reorganisation plan - which would give TWA's employees a 45
per cent stake in the airline in exchange for wage concessions, with
unsecured creditors taking the remaining 55 per cent - cannot be
implemented.
The proposal comes a week after inconclusive talks between the PGBC and Mr
Icahn, and does not have the TWA owner's agreement. TWA said yesterday the
proposal was 'under review'.
Meanwhile, the PGBC said it had informed the carrier's unions of the scheme
and they were examining the plan. Most participants in the pension schemes
would get full benefits under the proposal, although some fund members could
face reduced benefits.
Earlier yesterday, the carrier revealed a Dollars 3.2m loss for August after
tax. The operating deficit was slightly larger, at Dollars 7.49m, although
this was a considerable improvement on the Dollars 28.7m which the carrier
lost in the previous month.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
