<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Move to end power plant stoppage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION officials will meet shop stewards this morning in an attempt to
resolve an unofficial walkout by more than 2,000 workers that has halted
construction of the Enron gas-fired power plant, Teeside.
The workers - employed by the main contractor, Wimpey, and nearly 20
subcontractors - walked out on Monday in a protest over safety standards.
Enron Power Corporation said the safety issues had been addressed, but the
workers refused to return until Monday unless they received full payment for
the hours they had lost. The company had offered them 10 hours' money each.
Enron has warned that they are in breach of agreements and are risking
dismissal. Teesside officials of the main unions involved will today urge
the workers to return to work immediately.
Nuclear Electric, the state-owned power station operator in England and
Wales, intends to be viewed 'as a private sector investment' for its next
programme of station construction after 1994, Mr John Collier, its chairman,
said yesterday.
</TEXT>
