<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Wetherspoon flotation to raise Pounds 24m
for pubs expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JD WETHERSPOON, the London chain of pubs which feature cheap real ale and no
music, will offer shares worth Pounds 24m when it is floated shortly on the
stock exchange - a higher figure than initially expected.
The group is expected to have a market capitalisation of between Pounds 40m
to Pounds 45m.
A pathfinder prospectus, published yesterday, said the shares would be
placed with institutional investors, with an as yet unspecified number of
shares available for financial intermediaries.
Dealing will start about a week after the final prospectus is published,
which is expected in about a fortnight.
The company will raise at least Pounds 18m and existing shareholders are
expected to raise Pounds 6m.
Mr Tim Martin, 37, who founded the rapidly-expanding chain, is not selling
any shares leaving him with about 25 per cent of the company post-flotation.
The company has 44 outlets within the M25 and will use the proceeds from the
flotation to develop a further 18 sites for which it has obtained planning
and licensing permission.
</TEXT>
