<DATE>921009
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Banks refuse to offer Jubilee Line cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CANARY WHARF's bankers refused yesterday to make a no-strings offer of cash
to build the extension to London Underground's Jubilee Line, making it
almost inevitable that the project will not go ahead.
The 11 banks, which met yesterday, had already made an offer of Pounds 390m
conditional on civil servants moving to Canary Wharf, the failed development
in London's Docklands. The government does not regard that as a proper offer
under the terms it laid down earlier this year.
A government adviser said: 'I do not understand why the Canary Wharf
administrators have been claiming that the banks made an offer of funds for
the line, because they really had not.'
The government has said that the extension would go ahead only if the
private sector contributed Pounds 400m to the Pounds 1.6bn cost. Under the
terms, that contribution must not depend on any form of government support,
such as rent from a ministry.
The bankers had been hoping that the Department of the Environment would
relocate its main office to Canary Wharf. The department is now likely to
move its civil servants to empty government buildings in Whitehall. 'It
would have been utterly uncommercial of us to remove the condition of the
civil servants moving to Canary Wharf,' a banker said.
However, Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, insisted yesterday
that no decision had yet been taken on the department's relocation, and
emphasised again that the judgment would be made on the basis of value for
money.
If the Tube extension is abandoned, the administrators of Canary Wharf will
have enormous difficulty in finding tenants for the Pounds 1.5bn
development, the bankers said. One option, one of the bankers said, would be
to mothball most of the 15 buildings until the property market recovered.
London Regional Transport is making a last-ditch attempt to save the Jubilee
Line extension. It has commissioned a study from London Economics, the
research group, on the net costs of the line to the government, taking
account of indirect and direct tax revenues generated by the construction
project and social security savings.
It estimates the net costs at Pounds 972m, even without a contribution from
the private sector. However, the Treasury is understood to be unimpressed by
the argument.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 14
</PAGE>
