<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Labour attack on public spending cuts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, Labour leader, yesterday accused the government of preparing
to use the sterling crisis as an excuse for cuts in public spending.
In a letter to Mr John Major, he renewed his demand for the prime minister
to spell out the events leading up to sterling's exit from the European
exchange rate mechanism.
'I understand your keenness to draw a line under these events, but these are
questions which must be answered,' he said.
'We have a right to know the truth because Black Wednesday is clearly going
to be used by you and your ministers as the scapegoat for the imminent
abandonment of Tory election pledges on public expenditure - pledges which
you were always intending to abandon. Indeed, the round of ministerial
discussions on spending cuts began well before the sterling crisis.'
Labour later demanded that the prime minister outline an immediate 'national
recovery programme' in his speech to the Tory conference tomorrow.
The challenge was issued at a news conference by Labour's economics team led
by Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor.
</TEXT>
