<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Big rise reported in receiverships
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH companies are continuing to close down in record numbers, according
to new figures from KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountants.
Reporting a further big rise in the number of companies going into
receivership, Mr Tim Hayward, KPMG head of corporate recovery, said there
was still no sign of the economy emerging from recession.
According to KPMG, 1,059 companies were placed in the hands of receivers in
the three months to the end of September. The total represented a jump of
nearly 12 per cent from the 948 recorded in the previous three months.
South-east England took the brunt of the closures, accounting for about 52
per cent. The least affected regions were south Wales and Scotland. The
sector worst affected was manufacturing, followed by construction, financial
services and retailing.
Mr Hayward said a 'dramatic cut' in interest rates was needed to help to
stem the tide of business failures.
He added: 'Unless the government risks its commitment to reduce inflation
and introduces a dramatic reduction in interest rates in order to bring
about an increase in consumer confidence, I cannot see recovery happening in
the near future.'
Mr Hayward warned that exporters would continue to struggle throughout next
year.
