<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party at Brighton: EC environment rules
will stay, Howard says
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community directives on environmental standards would not be
abandoned as part of the government's work on subsidiarity, or minimum
interference by the EC Commission, Mr Michael Howard, the environment
secretary, said yesterday.
Mr Howard, speaking after his conference address, said it was hard to see
any directives that should be repealed, although there were some that should
be reviewed.
He emphasised that the environment was an area in which many of the issues
crossed national boundaries and he indicated that even directives that were
less obviously trans-European, such as those on beaches and on drinking
water quality, would remain.
However, he added that it was now unlikely that the Commission would
legislate in some areas where it had planned to do so, for example on
standards in zoos across the EC.
Mr Howard's defence of the Commission's role in environmental issues was
matched in his conference speech by his emphasis on its duties in ensuring
proper enforcement of EC directives by all the member states, as included in
the Maastricht treaty.
The representatives warmly applauded his comment: 'I'm getting sick and
tired of taking lectures from countries who don't take a blind bit of notice
of existing laws themselves'.
He suggested that the drive for stricter enforcement might end 'the cynical
charade of countries signing up to new laws to catch headlines at home when
they have not the slightest intention of putting them into effect'.
Mr Howard is to receive a report at the EC summit which is to be held in
Edinburgh in December from Mr Karel van Miert, the acting environment
commissioner, on whether member states of the community are complying with
EC legislation.
Next month the UK is to host a conference for environmental inspectors from
across Europe that is intended to establish a common approach to enforcing
the EC's directives on the environment.
</TEXT>
