<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / President handed tax bill problem
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Senate last night handed President George Bush a tricky political
problem, less than a month before the presidential election, by passing a
Dollars 27bn tax bill that he may feel obliged to veto.
Mr Bush supports the core of the bill, which includes the creation of 50
urban and rural enterprise zones to promote investment, an increase in the
tax-deductible income ceilings for those with personal pensions, and a
repeal of the special tax on certain luxury items, such as yachts and furs,
though not cars.
However, the bill also contains several small tax increases - on moving
expense allowances, on securities dealers and on high-income retired people
 -which run counter to the president's renewed election promise not to raise
taxes 'ever, ever.'
With the House of Representatives already adjourned and the Senate about to
be, Mr Bush need not formally exercise the veto but could simply not sign
the bill, a tactic known as the pocket veto.
Either way, Senator Robert Dole, Republican minority leader in the Senate,
predicted the bill would not become law.
The loss of the enterprise zones would be seen as a defeat for the
president's commitment to improve the inner cities.
He might blame his action, or inaction, on the Democratic-controlled
Congress, but a portrayal of the country's poor as suffering by his desire
to preserve tax breaks for the rich would put him where he does not want to
be - on the political defensive.
Reuter adds from Washington: Governor Bill Clinton, the Democratic
presidential candidate, received the endorsement yesterday of nearly 600
economists, including nine Nobel prize winners.
They said they liked his plan to revitalise the US economy through
government spending and tax breaks for business investment.
</TEXT>
