<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Solicitors tackle race bias
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE LAW Society
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the governing body for solicitors in England and Wales - is proposing to
amend its rule book to make sexual and racial discrimination by solicitors a
disciplinary offence.
The society said it had decided to make the move because 'discrimination
continues on a worrying scale against black trainees and qualified
solicitors'.
The new rule will add to existing equal-opportunity principles in the
profession's code of practice, by requiring law firms and legal departments
to adopt and operate an anti-discrimination policy.
The society said that would force solicitors to address the issue and
examine practices on recruitment and dealings with ethnic minorities. Firms
will be free to develop their own anti-discrimination policies or adopt a
specimen society policy that includes targets for employing ethnic
minorities.
Small firms should have at least one ethnic-minority lawyer and large firms
should have at least 10 per cent of trainees and 5 per cent of other lawyers
of ethnic-minority origin. Large firms are expected to meet the 10 per cent
trainee target by the end of 1995.
According to society statistics for last year, there were 10,423 firms of
solicitors in 14,997 offices in England and Wales and 487 local authorities
and 1,507 organisations employing solicitors. There were only 800 solicitors
from ethnic minorities.
However, 14 per cent of new students in 1990-91 were from ethnic minorities
and the figure has been rising steadily.
The society emphasised that the targets were not quotas and could not be
enforced. Adherence to the policy, though, will be taken into account during
routine monitoring, which from 1994 will have to take place in firms
authorised to take trainees.
The society said discrimination on grounds of sex was almost entirely
directed against women in mid career, principally after the birth of
children.
It said it had anecdotal evidence of women being asked unlawful questions at
interview about whether they were planning to have children.
The proposals are being put out to the profession for consultation. The
society has made clear that it intends to have the new rules in place by
early next year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
