FT  09 OCT 92 / M and S acts on Sunday trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW PROPOSALS for re-forming Sunday trading laws in England and Wales, put
forward by Marks and Spencer and other leading retailers, are under
consideration by the government.
The so-called M and S proposals, presented this week to Mr Peter Lloyd, Home
Office minister, combine a plan to deregulate weekday shopping with a call
to permit convenience stores of up to 3,000 sq ft to trade on Sundays
with-out restrictions on hours.
It would also allow do-it-yourself stores, garden centres and other
leisure-related outlets regardless of size to open on Sundays.
To forestall opposition from large food retailers, it is suggested that they
should be permitted to trade on the four Sundays before Christmas.
Backers of the proposals are believed to include C&amp;A, Burtons, Next, Sears,
Gateway Food Markets, The Co-operative Wholesale Society, and Open, a group
of smaller convenience stores jointly promoting their interests.
Mr Morton Middleditch, chairman of Open, said the proposals were designed to
maintain a distinction between weekdays and Sundays while recognising
weekend shopping needs.
Prospects of early legislation appear to be receding, with senior government
figures suggesting that moves to bring forward a potentially divisive bill
would meet resistance while the question of Europe tops the agenda.
</TEXT>
