<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Company failures rise sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH companies are continuing to close down in record numbers, according
to new figures from KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountants.
Reporting a further big rise in the number of companies going into
receivership, Mr Tim Hayward, KPMG's head of corporate recovery, said there
was still no sign that the economy was starting to emerge from recession.
According to KPMG, 1,059 companies were placed in the hands of receivers in
the three months to the end of September. The total represented a jump of
nearly 12 per cent from the 948 recorded in the previous three months.
South-east England took the brunt of the closures, accounting for about 52
per cent of all reported company failures. The least affected regions were
south Wales and Scotland. The sector worst affected by corporate failures
was manufacturing, followed by construction, financial services and
retailing.
Mr Hayward said that a 'dramatic cut' in interest rates was needed to help
to stem the tide of business failures.
He added: 'Unless the government risks its commitment to reduce inflation
and introduces a dramatic reduction in interest rates in order to bring
about an increase in consumer confidence, I cannot see recovery happening in
the near future.'
Mr Hayward warned that exporters would continue to struggle throughout next
year, in spite of the apparent lifeline that the pound's departure from the
European ex-change rate mechanism had offered.
He said: 'The underlying problem of the economic downturn in their markets
remains, and exporters in the UK will continue to find it difficult to make
sales in foreign markets.'
</TEXT>
