<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party at Brighton: Opposition quick to
challenge PM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OPPOSITION parties were quick to highlight what they saw as the weakened
government commitment on inflation in Mr Norman Lamont's speech, but then
used the chancellor's explanation of the new strategy as an occasion for
reviving their own economic remedies.
Labour then challenged Mr John Major to use his conference speech today to
announce a national recovery programme, comprising moves to restore business
confidence, to stimulate the housing market, and to remove the fear of
unemployment.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said that none of Mr Lamont's
targets was new 'except his clear abandonment of zero inflation', while Mr
Alan Beith, the Liberal Democrat spokesman, accused the chancellor of being
vague both about inflation and about interest rates.
'Mr Lamont's chancellorship is so bankrupt that the only alternative he can
offer to the policy that has failed is an earlier policy that has also
failed,' Mr Brown said.
'There was not one mention of the unemployed, of bankruptcies or
repossessions in a speech from Mr Lamont that was more intent on saving his
job than saving the jobs of others,' Mr Brown said.
Speaking on BBC radio, Mr Beith attacked Mr Lamont for not replacing
sterling's membership of the ERM with anti-recession measures and the
announcement that the Bank of England would be independent. Labour attacked
Mr Lamont on public spending, warning that the tough spending round would
delay recovery and increase unemployment.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, accused the government of using the
sterling crisis as an excuse for public spending cuts. He wrote to the prime
minister, demanding he make public more details about the events leading up
to the pound's suspension from the ERM, since that was a 'scapegoat' for
abandoning Tory election pledges.
</TEXT>
