<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party at Brighton: Thatcher fails to sink
ship of state
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WITH HER Exocet already fired on to the front pages of the national press,
Baroness Thatcher steamed in to the Conservatives' Brighton conference
yesterday to gauge the damage.
Her reconnaissance mission must have reached painful conclusions. For while
her fiercely derisory attack on Mr John Major's European policy - ironically
in The European newspaper - had clearly holed the Tory ship of state, it had
equally plainly failed to sink it.
As she swept imperiously to the platform, those of her supporters capable of
objective analysis must have detected subtle changes in her reception.
The standing ovation she received roughly matched the decibels of last year,
but its duration was a paltry three minutes - a 60 per cent devaluation of
the nine she recorded in Blackpool. A good third of the hall - most
ostentatiously the bulk of the platform - remained seated.
It was clear too that the wily choreographers of conference management had
also learnt some tricks.
Lady Thatcher arrived at the start of a lacklustre debate on the environment
and was placed between the uncharismatic Leader of the Commons, Mr Tony
Newton, and the all-but-unknown Lord Strathclyde: well below the salt.
Mr Major, meanwhile, was nowhere in sight.
When the cries of 'speech' started up, Sir Norman Fowler was swiftly at her
side to record the ritual modest refusal. Equally rapidly, the conference
chairman relayed her decision to the hall.
Token resistance was manifest in the waving of the odd Union Jack, a hastily
scribbled banner labelled 'Come Back' and another, more apposite perhaps,
inscribed simply: 'Help.' But it was quickly over.
Pitting her own fiercely loyal personal following against the Tories'
time-honoured obsession with unity before ideology, Lady Thatcher was
playing a high-risk game.
And while she has yet to pass her sell-by date, the reception she received
must have served as a stark reminder that even the best-known political
brand names have a limited shelf life.
Furthermore, the conference was plainly keen to communicate its own message
to the former leader.
When Mr Michael Howard offered Mr Major a compliment - 'If ever a man has
earned our loyalty, he has' - the applause was out of all proportion to the
blandness of the sentiment.
Just before the economy debate, Mr Major's arrival was greeted with
exaggerated effusiveness. A token kiss was exchanged.
Yet it was a doughty lady delegate from Cornwall who tapped the conference's
soul when she warned, to thunderous applause: 'There are enough speculators
and media commentators rocking the boat, we do not expect the elders of our
own party to do so, too.'
Unchastened, she may have been. But Lady Thatcher, nonetheless, felt obliged
to offer a token clap.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
