<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Jobs market statistics
encourage Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices ended higher across the board in busy trading yesterday in
the wake of a rise in bond prices and some welcome good news from the jobs
market, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 23.78 at 3,176.03, near
its high for the day. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 finished
up 3.49 at 407.74, while the Amex composite ended 0.13 higher at 367.01 and
the Nasdaq composite 4.69 higher at 573.89. Turnover on the NYSE was heavy
at 204m shares, and rises outpaced declines by 1047 to 648.
The market posted early gains following unexpectedly good news from the jobs
market. Government figures released yesterday showed that weekly state
unemployment insurance claims fell by 24,000 in the week which ended on
September 26.
The decline went against expectations as analysts had been predicting
another rise in weekly claims, and some investors seized on the data as an
indication that conditions in the labour market may be improving.
Although shares fell back later in the morning and flirted with negative
territory around midday, a series of late afternoon computer buy programs,
apparently triggered by the rebound in previously-weak bond prices, provided
the market with a strong lift just before the close. Among individual
stocks, Fannie Mae (Federal National Mortgage Association) jumped Dollars 1
3/8 to Dollars 64 3/4 in heavy trading after the company reported net income
of Dollars 412.9m in the third quarter, the 19th consecutive record quarter
for the group.
USAir climbed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 12 3/8 in turnover of more than 1m
shares after announcing that it had reached a settlement with striking
machinists.
The carrier said that 60 per cent of its service was back to normal
yesterday, and that a full service would be resumed by Monday.
Compaq rose Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 36 1/4 in turnover of 2m shares after
the computer company said its operating earnings in the third quarter would
be better than in the second.
Westinghouse Electric fell Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 14 3/4 after it
predicted that third quarter earnings would come in below 35 cents a share.
The company is also expected to take a charge of between Dollars 60m and
Dollars 100m on its investment in the discount drugstore chain, Phar-Mor.
Best Buy rose Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 26 1/4 on news that the retailer's
sales in September rose by 105 per cent to Dollars 156m. Another retail
group to report strong monthly sales was Wal-Mart Stores, up Dollars  1/2 at
Dollars 58.
Canada
IN TORONTO, gains in financial services and mining led stocks higher. The
TSE-300 composite index climbed 21.86 points or 0.68 per cent to 3,237.22,
and advancing issues edged out declines 251 to 246.
Volume was 26.3m shares worth CDollars 296.5m as against 33.3m shares worth
CDollars 376.6m previously.
The financial services sub-group gained 1.46 per cent on index, mining was
up 1.67 per cent, and consumer products rose 1.45 per cent.
Industrial products and energy posted smaller gains, while golds were off
moderately.
