<DOCNO>FT924-14479</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJIBOAEGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921009
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Chancellor moves to plug economic policy gap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Lamont's new monetary policy won few fans in Brighton yesterday.
The Conservative Conference gave the chancellor a brief standing ovation
that was loyally correct but far from enthusiastic, while the City's
immediate response was to mark sterling down by 2 pfennigs.
But the policy to fill the gaping hole in monetary discipline caused by
withdrawal from the European exchange rate mechanism contains two
potentially far-reaching innovations.
For the first time, a British government is setting an explicit inflation
target: of 1 per cent to 4 per cent for retail prices excluding mortgage
interest payments.
In a nation where policymaking is normally shrouded in secrecy, the
chancellor has promised to make monetary policy more accountable. If
inflation moves outside the targeted range, Mr Lamont has committed the
government to giving a full explanation to parliament and the markets of
what has gone wrong and how it plans to correct matters.
The Treasury and the Bank of England hope these elements will help establish
credibility. For in other aspects the plans in Mr Lamont's speech and in a
letter to Mr John Watts, the chairman of the Commons Treasury and Civil
Service committee, are a rerun of Tory policy in the mid 1980s.
Then as now, policy was guided by a number of monetary indicators and
tempered by Treasury judgment. That approach was abandoned in 1987 by Mr
Nigel Lawson in favour of shadowing the D-Mark, then replaced with
sterling's ill-fated membership of the ERM.
Mr Lamont promised yesterday that the government would look at monetary
aggregates; asset prices, including house prices; and the exchange rate in
determining when and by how much it should alter interest rates. That will
be backed by 'the tightest control of public spending'.
But the chancellor's letter to Mr Watts emphasised that there would be no
question of making monetary policy on automatic pilot. Judgment will affect
the very cornerstone of policy. 'The strength or weakness of the economy
will affect the pace' at which the UK moves towards its long-term objective
on inflation.
Similarly, on the exchange rate, there will be no target range nor any
shadowing of another currency. On the other hand, the government will not
let the exchange rate 'go where it will'. The chancellor said: 'The test is
whether we believe a movement in the exchange rate (as defined by the
sterling exchange-rate index) or a particular level of it, sustained for a
period, is likely to jeopardise the inflation objective.'
Mr Lamont is wary of the indicators that will help to underpin his policies.
M0, the narrow measure of money supply which the government targets, is
behaving itself and is close to the centre of its 0 per cent to 4 per cent
target growth range. His letter admits that M0, which comprises mainly notes
and coin in circulation, 'is limited to providing a timely guide to current
behaviour in the economy'.
Past experience suggests that it would be unwise to establish a formal
target for M4, the broad money measure. Instead, Mr Lamont will announce
'monitoring ranges' for M4 beyond which its movement would be 'increasing
cause for concern' in next month's Autumn Statement.
The Bank and Treasury will study various weighted broad money indices, such
as the Divisia index, which has followers in the City. Mr Lamont said it was
too early, though, to give such measures a formal place in the way monetary
conditions are assessed. He will also monitor asset prices, particularly
when house prices are falling or accelerating sharply.
Mr Lamont's guarded exposition of his new policy reflects a realisation
among policymakers that there is no magic formula for operating monetary
policy. That was acknowledged last night by Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the
governor of the Bank of England, in a speech in Cambridgeshire.
Yesterday's explanations of the mechanics of the new monetary policy gave
the markets little clear guidance. Indeed, any trader watching the
chancellor's speech on television could be forgiven for thinking that the UK
economy was again to be steered by seat-of-the-pants judgments.
The inflation targets detailed in the chancellor's letter showed that
monetary policy would be tight, and tended to bear out Mr Lamont's claim
that the government intends to take no risks with inflation.
By past standards, the inflation targets are ambitious. The annual rate of
retail price inflation, excluding mortgage interest payments, was 4.2 per
cent in August and has never been lower than 3.1 per cent. On the other
hand, the economy is so depressed that an underlying inflation rate of 2 per
cent or less 'in the long term' should be achievable.
In the short term, however, there is no way that the speakers who called for
interest rate cuts of 2, 3 or 5 percentage points yesterday will have their
wishes granted. In one important respect, leaving the ERM has not changed
policy. The inflation targets mean that a substantial cut in UK interest
rates will have to wait for a clear easing of monetary conditions in
Germany.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
