<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Lamont's letter
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The main points of proposals to the Commons Treasury and Civil Service
committee
The European exchange rate mechanism: Britain will resume membership but
only when a number of conditions have been satisfied, including an end to
turbulence on currency markets and a narrowing in the difference in interest
rates between Germany and the US. Those conditions are unlikely to be
satisfied soon.
Inflation: Britain needs to aim for a rate of inflation in the long term of
2 per cent or less. For the remainder of the current parliament, Britain
should keep underlying inflation (based on the year-on-year growth in the
retail-prices index, excluding mortgage interest payments) within a range of
1 per cent to 4 per cent.
Special circumstances affecting prices: We have to acknowledge that events
outside our control may take us temporarily outside the range. That could
arise, for example, if there were a sharp movement in the terms of trade,
particularly through commodity prices.
Monetary policy: The government will judge inflationary trends according to
a wide range of factors, including domestic monetary targets. There will be
a general emphasis on reaching a judgment on inflationary trends and whether
the government's objectives are likely to be achieved.
Exchange rate: The Treasury will give full weight to the exchange rate in
assessing monetary conditions, but there will be no target range for the
pound. Equally, the exchange rate will not be allowed to go where it will.
The lesson from the 1980s is that exchange rates can move a long way,
upwards or downwards, if markets come to believe the authorities do not
care.
Narrow measure of money supply (M0): The target for M0 - year-on-year growth
of 0 to 4 per cent - will be retained. M0 has proved a reliable indicator
and its relationship with current spending in the economy has proved
remarkably stable.
Broad money measure (M4): M4 contains important information on monetary
conditions. But experience indicates that the relationship between these
aggregates and either money GDP or future inflation is not close enough to
justify establishing M4 as a formal target. The government is to give some
idea in the Autumn Statement of the values for the growth of M4 which may
indicate a build-up of inflationary pressures.
Composite monetary indicators: It is premature to give such indices a formal
place in the system of monetary assessment, but the Bank of England and
Treasury will be looking at them further.
Other indicators of inflation: The Treasury will monitor money market
interest rates, and asset prices including house prices. Officials will pay
particular attention to periods when house prices are falling or
accelerating sharply.
Fiscal policy: If industry is to be able to take advantage of the
opportunities the lower exchange rate has now presented, it will be
essential to keep tight control over public spending and borrowing. The
government will be seeking to maintain firm downward pressure on the growth
of public-sector pay. This will also ensure that the public sector matches
industry's efforts to contain its own wage costs and so hang on to the
improved competitiveness. The government will also pursue a tight policy on
public spending.
</TEXT>
