<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Egypt presses Israelis on talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL announced a concession on Middle East peace talks last night after a
visit at short notice by Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said Israel had agreed that Palestinians from
outside the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip could take part in regional
talks that run in parallel to the main peace negotiations. But the
Palestinians must not be members of the Palestine National Council or from
East Jerusalem, Mr Peres added.
The shift was seen as a gesture towards improving the atmosphere at the
bilateral negotiations under way for almost a year between Israel and,
respectively, Syria, the Palestinians, Jordan and Lebanon.
On his return to Cairo Mr Moussa said he expected the Israeli team
negotiating self-rule with the Palestinians to be given new orders to push
the talks forward.
Mr Moussa apparently made an effort to persuade Israeli leaders to make
commitments to withdraw from occupied Arab lands as a way to ensure progress
at the peace negotiations, which are due to resume in Washington later this
month.
'We are trying to build confidence,' Mr Moussa said.
