FT  09 OCT 92 / Dos Santos holds out olive branch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANGOLAN President Jose Eduardo dos Santos last night urged his civil war foe
Jonas Savimbi to put aside doubts about last week's elections and help
rebuild the country. He said he was seeking a meeting with Mr Savimbi, who
has retreated to a stronghold 500km from Luanda.
The president's conciliatory remarks came as the US said it had assurances
from the Unita rebel movement that Mr Savimbi, who alleged fraud in the
elections, would abide by the result and not resume the war.
In his first statement since the poll, Mr dos Santos said there was a lot of
anxiety in the country and 'anybody returning to war would meet the
condemnation of the international community and the Angolan people.'
He said the sympathisers of Unita and other parties 'should know that they
have an indispensable role to play in the reconstruction of the country.'
In Washington, Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen, said Mr Savimbi's
aides had said he would concede defeat. 'I've had some private assurances
from some senior associates of Mr Savimbi in the last days that they will
abide by the results,' Mr Cohen said.
