<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / International Company News: McDonnell Douglas in novel
health deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MCDONNELL Douglas, the financially stretched US aerospace group, yesterday
came up with an innovative means of protecting its balance sheet from the
impact of new accounting rules for retirees' health benefits.
The plan, which covers retirees who do not belong to a union, involves the
replacement of company-funded health care coverage with a scheme funded by
the retirees themselves - though much of the cost will be met by a special
trust fund set up by the company.
The financial key to the scheme, which will last until at least 1996, is the
establishment of a special trust which will draw on a surplus in the
company's pension fund, estimated at Dollars 2.2bn in December 1991.
McDonnell said that the surplus would be reduced by about Dollars 300m.
All US companies face large non-cash write-offs over the next year as they
adopt Standard Financial Accounting Statement 106, which requires them to
show their future healthcare obligations to retirees, rather than what they
are actually paying out in any given year.
McDonnell said yesterday that its scheme would reduce its estimated FASB 106
write off from Dollars 1.2bn-Dollars 1.8bn - almost half shareholders'
equity - to about Dollars 600m to Dollars 700m. It explained that retirees
enrolling in its new plan would receive a one-time supplement - drawn from
the special pension benefit trust - which could be used to pay for coverage
identical to that offered under the company scheme.
The company said the amount of the supplement, after taxes, equalled almost
all of the cost of the premium, so 'most retirees will have little, if any,
new costs that are not covered by the supplemental pension benefit'.
The complexities of the scheme may cause anxiety among McDonnell employees,
although the company argued yesterday that its commitment to the plan until
1996 meant greater security for retirees, since up till now it has had the
power to modify its benefits programme.
Termination of the company-funded healthcare plan will allow McDonnell to
cut its cash spending on retiree health care, which it said had more than
quadrupled in the last decade.
The programme affects some 20,000 retirees and will involve a further 50,000
employees when they retire.
McDonnell Douglas's balance sheet has been strained ever since it spent some
Dollars 4bn to develop its new MD-11 wide-bodied civilian aircraft. It lacks
the funds to develop a larger aircraft, the MD-12 and has been seeking Asian
equity finance, so far without success.
</TEXT>
