<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Opt-out school funds squeezed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's campaign to persuade schools in England and Wales to opt
out of local-authority control ran into further trouble yesterday with the
release of an Education Department letter warning of a squeeze in capital
funding for opted-out schools.
Mrs Ann Taylor, the shadow education secretary, who published the letter,
said: 'This shows that the long-term future of grant-maintained status will
involve underfunding.'
The letter instructs opted-out (grant-maintained) schools not to submit bids
for capital spending on libraries, sixth-form blocks, sports halls or
performing-arts facilities. 'In the climate of limited funds there are
greater demands to be met,' it says.
It will cause considerable disappointment to grant-maintained schools, many
of which opted out in the expectation that funding for such projects would
be more readily available from the government than from local authorities.
The letter goes on to tell grant-maintained schools, whose capital funding
comes directly from the government, that because of the tight
public-spending round and the growth of the opted-out sector 'the government
is unable to offer schools the guarantee that the (existing funding) formula
will continue or that funds can be rolled over to the next financial year.'
Head teachers told their pay review body yesterday that the introduction of
performance-related pay for teachers would be a 'recipe for discontent'
unless an extra 5 per cent was given to each successful school.
The National Association of Head Teachers said it had 'substantial
reservations' about merit pay, but would defer judgment until it had studied
any scheme piloted in schools.
The teachers' pay review body will outline proposals in January for
extending performance pay.
In an initial paper, it favoured a scheme rewarding academically successful
schools with a cash bonus. However, Mr John Patten, education secretary, has
criticised the idea, calling instead for individual payments for successful
teachers so all have an incentive to improve their performance.
Mr David Hart, NAHT general secretary, said ministers and the review body
should agree to abandon performance pay it if became 'evident that it will
not work'.
</TEXT>
