<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Protection urged for EC-aided projects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT economic regeneration programmes that benefit from EC aid should
be protected from public-expenditure cuts, Mr Bruce Millan, EC Commissioner
for the regions, said last night.
In a lecture to the Audit Commission, Mr Millan warned that cuts in
government spending on such projects might break the 'additionality' rule,
part of the legislation governing the use of EC structural funds. The rule
forbade the use of such funds to replace government expenditure.
In February, the government gave undertakings that allowed the release of EC
regional fund money withheld because the Commission was not satisfied that
the additionality criterion would be met.
However, Mr Millan warned that the detailed implementation of the
undertakings was not yet 'fully clear'. He added that a strict application
of the additionality rule would mean that any funding of joint projects by
national governments should be 'exempt from public expenditure cuts'.
Mr Millan reiterated his commitment to a bigger role for the regions in
Europe, particularly in promoting EC economic development. The Commission
would develop its policy of dealing directly with regions in funding
regeneration programmes.
'Subsidiarity does not stop in London or in any other national capital,' he
said. 'Devolving more power to the regions to devise and implement their own
economic development strategies will give better results.'
</TEXT>
