<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / May Day holiday could be abolished
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE May Day bank holiday might be abolished as early as 1995, Mrs Gillian
Shephard, the employment secretary, said yesterday, Bethan Hutton writes.
She said that the holiday, celebrated by many countries as Labour Day, had
been forced on Britain by the TUC.
One possible replacement would be an October holiday to commemorate the
Battle of Trafalgar but Mrs Shephard said her personal preference was for an
extra day added to the late August bank holiday, which might be less
disruptive to business than an isolated day. She promised to hold
consultations on the issue.
Any change would not apply to Scotland, which has had a May Day holiday for
longer than the rest of the UK.
Mrs Shephard also said that if an EC 48-hour working time directive were
adopted, the government would challenge it in the European court of justice.
'Despite the improvements we have won, we remain fundamentally opposed in
principle to this directive,' she said.
She later hinted that wages councils might be abolished in the Industrial
Relations Bill expected to go before parliament later this year.
Mrs Shephard said: 'Wages councils and mechanisms like that have no place in
today's labour market.'
</TEXT>
