<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Lord Moore to head 'green' energy trust
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD MOORE, the former cabinet minister, will be appointed within two weeks
as first chairman of the new Energy Saving Trust, one of the main planks in
the government's environmental policy.
His appointment ends a long hunt by the Department of the Environment for a
suitable candidate. The DoE has been criticised for the slow progress in
setting up the trust, which featured prominently in the Conservative general
election manifesto and in the government's statement in Rio at the Earth
Summit in June.
The trust, a limited company, was founded to identify energy-efficiency
projects in which British Gas and regional electricity companies will
invest. It is one of several proposals to help the UK meet internationally
agreed targets for reducing emissions of potentially harmful gases.
The trust will consider whether the costs of those investments should be
passed on to gas and electricity customers, which is ultimately the decision
of Offer and Ofgas, the industry regulators.
The delay in finding a chairman stalled the first three pilot projects that
British Gas was contemplating a year ago before its plans became subsumed in
proposals for the trust. It will now be possible to appoint a board of
directors that will include representatives of British Gas and the
electricity companies, as well as a majority of non-utility directors.
Lord Moore of Lower Marsh, once tipped as a possible successor to Margaret
Thatcher, left the political spotlight in 1988 when, as social security
minister, he became embroiled in the row over NHS reforms.
He had previously been a minister at the Department of Energy and later
financial secretary of the Treasury, where he was a vigorous free-market
proponent.
He is now executive chairman of the fund management arm of Credit Suisse.
The government hopes to keep the UK's emissions of carbon dioxide to within
157m-179m tons by the year 2000, compared to 160m in 1990, the Department of
Trade and Industry said yesterday.
The range reflects a number of developments in recent years, including new
proposals for more efficient gas-fired electricity generation, and
improvements in energy efficiency. It also reflects different assumptions
about both the level and structure of economic activity and about energy
prices.
</TEXT>
