<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Export boom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Steel's newest investment on Teesside is enjoying an increase in
exports, cushioning it against the recession in the UK construction
industry, Chris Tighe writes.
Yesterday Mr Barrie Cheetham (above), commercial director of British Steel's
general steels division, said the company anticipated keeping the mill fully
loaded 'into the planning horizon'.
The Pounds 82m mill, which makes beams and columns up to 27 metres long for
construction projects such as skyscrapers and bridges, has been working at
capacity since becoming fully operational in mid-summer.
The mill yesterday opened its doors for visits by UK and overseas customers.
It has substantially extended British Steel's range of heavy sections,
allowing it to win more export orders. The devaluation of the pound has also
helped it compete overseas.
Of its output, 85 per cent is being exported - mainly to the Far East and
central Europe. Its predecessor plant on Teesside was exporting half its
output two years ago. The proportion of exports has increased even though
the US construction industry, an important customer, has suffered a
downturn.
Mr Cheetham said structural sections was seen as one of British Steel's
strengths. 'Although we are in a recession, to have the benefit of a mill
like this is something our competitors would envy,' he said. 'With mills
like this we have the cost base, quality and project range to allow us to
compete very successfully in the export market.'
</TEXT>
