<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Launch of New FT Indices: Harmony dissidents claim support
from institutions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REBEL SHAREHOLDERS at Harmony Leisure are requisitioning an extraordinary
meeting to try to oust the directors of the loss-making restaurant and pub
group, following a 70 per cent increase in pre-tax losses.
Former hotelier Mr Andrew Martyr, the leader of the dissident group, said
attempts to install a new management team had been boosted by pledges of
support from institutional shareholders after the company announced losses
this week of Pounds 3.68m for the year to March 29.
'The institutions have decided all is not well and they are now supporting
us,' Mr Martyr said yesterday.
An EGM is expected to be held immediately after Harmony's annual meeting
next month.
Calls for management changes have gathered pace with the dramatic slide in
the share price, which has fallen from 79p to 6p since 1990.
'Shareholders have lost a considerable amount of money,' said Mr Martyr.
Queens Moat, the hotel group which has a 14.5 per cent stake in Harmony, has
expressed concern at the losses. Southend Property Holdings, with a 4 per
cent interest, confirmed it had been asked to support the rebels.
Both companies said they will wait to examine the final accounts, expected
to be published next week.
Mr Stanley Lever, managing director of Harmony, has vowed to fight any moves
to remove the existing board.
