<HEADLINE>
FT  09 OCT 92 / Indian brewer set to enter UK via Wiltshire takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR VIJAY Mallya, one of India's largest distillers and brewers, is set to
attempt an assault on the UK drinks distribution market via a takeover of
Wiltshire Brewery, the UK quoted drinks company.
Shares in the ailing west of England brewery, which has struggled to make a
profit from its Old Grumble, Stonehenge and Old Devil beers, were suspended
yesterday on the London Stock Exchange.
The takeover of Wiltshire will involve fresh equity via a share placing.
There will also be a subscription of new shares from a 'major overseas
brewing and spirits group' - believed to be Mr Mallya's family-controlled UB
Group - and possibly an injection of pubs from what Wiltshire calls a 'major
UK brewer'.
Wiltshire said yesterday that details of the deal will be announced before
October 16.
The deal would bring together one of the UK's smallest brewers, chaired by
Mr Graham Axford, a former managing director of corporate finance at James
Capel, and Mr Mallya, the subcontinent's biggest force in the drinks market.
UB imports and distributes Kingfisher beer to off-licences and Indian
restaurants throughout the country. It also has a joint venture with
Kent-based Shepherd Neame.
In India, however, UB - formally United Breweries of India - has expanded
beyond its brewing roots into a multinational conglomerate with interests in
distilling, petrochemical and engineering.
Mr Mallya is interested in using the Wiltshire vehicle to sell large volumes
of white spirits such as rum, gin and vodka to UK pubs.
In spite of winning a number of good beer awards, Wiltshire has been
loss-making for most of the seven years since it was bought out of
receivership in 1985.
Shareholders have yet to see their company's annual report for the 14 months
to November 1991, ostensibly the reason why the shares were suspended
yesterday.
Wiltshire went back to shareholders in 1991 - a year after joining the
Unlisted Securities Market - to finance the acquisition of pubs from Bass
soon after the government's beer orders triggered a sequence of pub swaps by
the large brewers.
Mr Mallya is likely to use the Wiltshire vehicle to develop a pub estate and
further develop his distribution company for importing products from the
group.
