FT  09 OCT 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An odiously sycophantic book on royal gardens - the present royals, that is
 -landed on my desk only last month and I binned it in disgust. In Royal
Gardens (BBC2, 8.30) Sir Roy Strong, art-historian and topiarist, takes an
historical journey through the gardens of the British royalty - Dutch too,
since tonight's opening programme includes Dutch William's wonderful garden
at Het Loo.
Not the least interesting thing over the next six weeks will be to see
whether Strong manages to tread royal turf and sniff regal lilies without
turning into a fawning nincompoop.
I Renounce War (9.30) continues BBC 2's series, 'War and Peace' with a
portrayal of the changing status of the pacifist in wartime since 1916 when
the Military Service Act introduced a conscience clause. One of the last
surviving conscientious objectors from the Great War describes his
experience of spending most of it in solitary confinement in Wormwood
Scrubs.
While we wait for the Bush-Clinton dialogues, BBC2 starts the ball rolling
with Campaign (11.15), a weekly series presenting the best and the worst of
the US election campaign coverage.
