<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / Rival bids emerge in coal sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROSPECT of a split among British Coal employees over how to mount a
buy-out of the company emerged yesterday as the Union of Democratic
Mineworkers and East Midlands Electricity confirmed plans to form a bidding
consortium.
The British Association of Colliery Management had earlier announced its
plans to purchase the company. Mr John Meads, general secretary, said last
night that rivalry would be 'unfortunate'. But he stressed that the ultimate
aim must be to preserve as much of British Coal as possible.
The UDM and East Midlands consortium is preparing plans for a buy-out that
would include a 20 per cent stake for employees. The consortium would be
willing to bid for the whole company, but would consider other structures if
the government preferred to break it up. One preference would be to split
British Coal into two equal sizes with a mix of deep and open-cast mining.
BACM believes British Coal should be sold as one piece to give it a viable
structure.
East Midlands and the UDM, who have been working on their plans for a year,
have established a steering group which includes Sir David White, deputy
chairman of the National Freight Corporation, itself the subject of a
successful buy-out in the early 1980s. Others members are Mr Dickson Mabon,
energy minister in the last Labour government, and Mr George Guise, former
director of Consolidated Gold Fields and adviser to Lady Thatcher.
The consortium hopes to attract two or three other members and is engaged in
talks with companies in mining production and equipment supply industries.
The government has said it wants privatisation to lead to an employee stake
in the business. Public money will be available to help employees put
together buy-out proposals.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
