<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / International Company News: Raytheon ahead 5.1% at Dollars
156m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RAYTHEON, the New England-based defence business which makes the Patriot
missile, yesterday announced a 5.1 per cent rise in third quarter net
income, even though profits in its important electronics division were lower
than a year ago.
The company reported net income of Dollars 156.1m, or Dollars 1.16 a share,
compared with Dollars 148.4m, or Dollars 1.12 a share, in the same period of
last year, on sales of Dollars 2.2bn, down from Dollars 2.35m.
Electronics, which includes the Patriot missile and the company's largest
business, saw lower sales and profits, which the company said reflected the
timing of key production orders, including one pending from Saudi Arabia for
Patriot fire units and missiles.
However, Mr Dennis Picard, chairman and chief executive, said earnings
benefited from improved profitability in energy and environmental
businesses, aircraft products and major appliances - despite a sluggish
economy and a slip in receipt of foreign contracts.
In the first nine months Raytheon made Dollars 465.1m, or Dollars 3.46 a
share, compared with Dollars 433.9m, or Dollars 3.29 a share, in 1991, while
sales were down from Dollars 6.84bn to Dollars 6.66bn.
