<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party at Brighton: Scots vote 'shows
backing for Union'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S distinctive identity and contribution to the United Kingdom must
be recognised, Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, told a conference fringe
meeting of the Monday Club yesterday.
Mr Lang said that the general election, when the Conservatives gained two
seats in Scotland rather than losing several as predicted, had been a 'vote
of confidence' in the Union, but warned: 'Dissatisfaction with the Union is
likely to emerge once again if there is insufficient recognition of
Scotland's status as a nation.'
'Far too many people believe that the United Kingdom and England are
synonymous,' he said.
'Significant measures' to strengthen the union and Scotland's place in it,
together with a new approach to Scotland's government, would emerge from the
stocktaking of the Union promised during the election campaign, Mr Lang
said.
He ruled out a national assembly, but said reform of local government, with
the introduction of powerful single-tier authorities, was central to the
stocktaking process. The Scottish Office should play a more visible part in
Scottish life and become more accessible. The conclusions of the stocktaking
are expected in the next few months.
Mr Lang admitted mistakes had been made during the Thatcher era in the
government's relationship with Scotland. 'Perhaps we have not been
sufficiently active in addressing Scotland's different priorities,' he said.
'There is no point in importing policy for the sake of it. More policy
should be home grown in Scotland and policy must be right for Scotland,' he
added.
Mr Lang said he was awaiting findings of a feasibility study on Scottish
water privatisation before making a decision. But in his speech he hinted he
would not be put off by opinion polls showing that most Scots oppose water
privatisation.
'Policymaking by opinion poll doesn't work,' he said, and added: 'I am not
afraid of being unpopular.'
</TEXT>
