FT  08 OCT 92 / US carriers seek delay in British air deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE three largest US airlines have told the Bush administration that British
Airways should only be allowed to complete its proposed Dollars 750m
investment in Virginia-based USAir once an 'open skies' regime between the
US and the UK is fully operational.
The airlines' latest position is set out in a letter to Mr Jeffrey Shane, US
assistant secretary of transportation for policy and international aviation.
It comes as talks between the UK and US governments have just restarted in
Washington over possible revisions to the bilateral agreement which governs
aviation arrangements between the two countries.
The airlines - American, United and Delta, with Federal Express, the largest
overnight package delivery company - say they 'were advised that the
administration's goal. . . in the discussions is to obtain a commitment for
a phased-in open skies regime over a yet to be defined timetable.'
But, they continue: 'If a 'phase-in' to full 'open skies' is the only avenue
available, the US must ensure that the BA-USAir transaction can be
implemented in full no earlier than the completion of the 'phase-in'. The US
must maintain this leverage to protect its vital trade interests.'
