<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / Wide backing forfoes of Canada's new constitution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OPPONENTS of Canada's proposed new constitution have opened a wide lead in
several key provinces, less than three weeks before a national referendum on
the constitutional package.
A Gallup poll published yesterday showed the No side backed by 53 per cent
of decided voters in British Columbia, 51 per cent in the three prairie
provinces and 46 per cent in Quebec. Support for the deal in these regions
is estimated at 30-36 per cent.
Doubts about the outcome of the October 26 referendum have already lifted
domestic interest rates and elicited warnings of further economic
turbulence. Mr Ted Newall, chief executive of Nova Corporation of Alberta,
one of the country's biggest energy and pipeline companies, warned on
Tuesday night that a No vote would mean, at best, five to 15 years of
economic and political uncertainty.
The constitutional package - the Charlottetown Agreement - is backed by all
three national parties, the leaders of all 10 provinces and the bulk of
Canada's business community.
They have been put on the defensive, however, by having to acknowledge that
the agreement is a compromise which gives no region or interest group
everything it wants.
Its critics - the most vociferous of whom include Quebec separatists,
western Canadian regional groups and women activists - have had the
advantage of highlighting the agreement's weaknesses.
The Yes side, which was slow to put its campaign into gear, expects to make
up ground over the next few weeks. It is taking comfort from the big
proportions of undecided voters - 22 per cent in Quebec and 17 per cent in
British Columbia.
</TEXT>
