<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RAFAH, GAZA STRIP
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAELI soldiers shot and wounded at least 90 Palestinians in the occupied
Gaza Strip yesterday during marches in support of a prisoner hunger strike,
Reuter reports from Rafah, Gaza Strip.
Soldiers fired live ammunition, plastic bullets and tear gas to disperse
several thousand demonstrators outside the Red Cross headquarters in Rafah
refugee camp. Palestinians threw stones and fire bombs in the fiercest
clashes in the Strip in five months.
One man was critically wounded in the head, hospital sources said. Another
was shot twice in the neck and one woman lost an eye. Seventy-two others
suffered light wounds.
In Mughazi camp, 15 protesters were wounded, four seriously, medical sources
said.
The army said 20 to 25 Palestinians were hurt, none seriously.
The protests were to back an 11-day-old hunger strike by thousands of Arab
prisoners demanding better conditions.
Israel says the strike is a political move to bolster the Palestinian
position at the peace talks.
