<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / El Al jet crash probe suffers a new setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL and PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ACCIDENT investigators yesterday recovered the 'black box' flight data
recorder from the El Al Boeing 747 cargo jet which crashed into two
Amsterdam housing blocks on Sunday, killing at least 250 people.
But Dutch officials warned that the flight recorder, which has been flown to
the Farnborough Accident Investigation Centre in the UK for decoding, was
badly damaged.
Investigators are hoping the device will provide some key data to pinpoint
the cause of the El Al disaster, although a Dutch transport ministry
official said they were 'rather pessimistic' on how much information it
would yield.
Piecing together the cause of the crash is proving extremely difficult.
Search teams have so far not found the separate cockpit voice recorder,
which could reveal the last conversations between the pilots before the
crash.
Adding to the investigators' difficulties, only one of the engines has been
found in a lake nine miles away from the crash site. This has raised the
possibility that earlier reports that both starboard engines had broken
loose from the aircraft were incorrect.
The Dutch transport ministry spokeswoman said the two large pieces of engine
found so far now appear to be two halves of the same outer starboard Pratt &amp;
Whitney engine. There was also no trace of fire. A spokeswoman for
Amsterdam's Schipol airport confirmed yesterday that three months ago the El
Al Boeing had reported an engine fire in mid-air during an incoming flight
to Amsterdam.
The Dutch government official said it was still too early to conclude that
only one engine had broken free. Investigators are using sonar equipment in
the lake where the engine pieces were found in case the second starboard
engine is there.
Original reports that both starboard engines had been torn away from the
aircraft suggested similarities with an accident in Taiwan last December
when a China Airlines 747 cargo aircraft, also powered by Pratt &amp; Whitney
engines, crashed after losing its two starboard engines.
The US Federal Aviation Authority (FAA) said yesterday it planned to issue
soon an airworthiness directive to airlines to inspect possible defects in
the engine mounts on older versions of the Boeing 747 jets.
But the FAA said the order would have gone out regardless of the Amsterdam
crash, adding there was no direct evidence in the Amsterdam or the Taiwan
disasters pointing to the cause of either crash being the fuse pins
connecting the engine struts to the wings.
Boeing issued a formal notification to 747 operators to check fuse pins on
Monday but had already discussed the issue at a meeting with airline
customers last month.
</TEXT>
