<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / US set to upgrade role in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US is expected to provide crucial intelligence and other support to the
new United Nations forces due to be deployed to protect aid convoys in
Bosnia.
It is expected that US officers will join a headquarters operation drawn
largely from the existing structure of Nato's German-based Northern Army
Group.
The main US contribution on the ground would be a field hospital, but it is
thought Washington may also provide heavy transport aircraft to help with
the deployment.
The move is significant both for the US, in committing even limited numbers
of military personnel to former Yugoslavia, and for the UN, in extending the
scope of peacekeeping operations to include intelligence-gathering.
US participation is understood to have been sealed despite initial French
reservations. The force will be commanded by France's General Philippe
Morillon, with Britain providing the largest number of troops.
The UK is expected initially to send more than the 1,800 troops. Its
concerns about command and control arrangements in Bosnia have been met by
plans to transfer a 'core' headquarters operation from the Northern Army
Group. Germany, which is part of this Nato grouping alongside the UK,
Holland and Belgium, will not take part because of its constitutional
constraints. The gap will be filled by France and others.
</TEXT>
